<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">Forget Donald Trump's plans to eliminate the U.S. Department of =
Education or allegations of fraud against Trump University: The real estate=
 executive has already poisoned public
 schools, according to American Federation of Teachers President Randi Wein=
garten, by fostering a toxic environment that encourages bullying.&nbsp;<o:=
p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">In a conference call with reporters on Thursday, Weingarten blas=
ted the real estate executive for his &quot;xenophobia&quot; and his &quot;=
promotion of violence.&quot; And she said that it's too
 late to turn back the clock on&nbsp;the negative effect he's already had o=
n public schools.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">&quot;My point is, he's already done tremendous damage to educat=
ion,&quot; Weingarten said during a conference call with reporters. &quot;H=
e's created an environment of scapegoating and demonizing.&nbsp;It
 is influencing children and it is influencing behavior in schools. It is m=
aking it much, much harder for us.&quot;&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"http://blog=
s.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12"><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-f=
amily: Calibri, sans-serif; color: blue; text-decoration: none;"><img borde=
r=3D"0" width=3D"126" height=3D"126" id=3D"_x0000_i1025" src=3D"cid:image00=
1.jpg@01D1A6E8.69F0FE80" alt=3D"electionslug_2016_126x126.jpg"></span></a><=
span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: b=
lack;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">Is there anything to back up Weingarten's assertion? Last month,=
 my colleague Evie Blad covered a survey conducted by the Southern Poverty =
Law Center showing that most teachers
 say their students=97many of them Muslim or the children of immigrants=97<=
a href=3D"http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/rulesforengagement/2016/04/donald_=
trumps_rhetoric_has_made_some_students_feel_unsafe_report_says.html" target=
=3D"_blank">have expressed fears about their
 fate after the election</a>. And 40 percent said they're afraid to teacher=
 their students about the election. However, that survey was not scientific=
.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">There have also been reports of incidents like&nbsp;<a href=3D"h=
ttp://www.cnn.com/2016/03/01/us/midwest-trump-school-chants/" target=3D"_bl=
ank">Donald Trump's name being chanted by fans</a>&nbsp;at
 a Wisconsin high school soccer game, along with &quot;build that wall&quot=
; and racial slurs.&nbsp;(Trump has pledged to halt illegal immigration fro=
m Mexico by building a wall along the southern border, and by making the Me=
xican government pay for it.) But in general, it's
 hard to statiscally identify exactly how Trump has or has not broadly infl=
uenced the climate of public schools.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">Make no mistake, Weingarten and Democratic Rep. Mark Pocan, who =
was also on the call, blasted Trump for his other positions on education to=
o. Weingarten said she was not surprised
 that one of Trump's high-profile surrogates is New Jersey Gov. Chris Chris=
tie, a Republican
<a href=3D"http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/state_edwatch/2015/08/gov_christi=
e_teachers_unions_need_a_punch_in_the_face_and_are_destructive.html" target=
=3D"_blank">
who has said teachers' unions need a punch in the face</a>.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p=
></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">&quot;What we're seeing is the presumptive nominee of the Republ=
ican Party be anti-teacher and anti-public education,&quot; the AFT preside=
nt said.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">Donald Trump hasn't taken many in-depth positions on K-12 during=
 the campaign.&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12=
/2016/05/donald_trump_education_policy_review.html" target=3D"_blank">But
 he has taken a few (relatively) clear positions on K-12</a>. He wants to e=
liminate the Common Core State Standards=97something the federal government=
 cannot do. And as Weingarten noted, he's said he wants to either severely =
cut or eliminate the Education Department=97at
 the same time, he declared in March that&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://blogs.edwe=
ek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2016/03/donald_trump_education_federal_priority=
.html" target=3D"_blank">education is one of the top three priorities for t=
he federal government</a>.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; colo=
r: black;">You might remember that both the AFT and the National Education =
Association moved pretty quickly to endorse former Secretary of State Hilla=
ry Clinton for the Democratic presidential
 nomination. That did not sit well with some members of the two unions, who=
 thought that there ought to have been
<a href=3D"http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2016/03/30/sanders-gets-educat=
ors-attention-despite-few-specifics.html" target=3D"_blank">
more consideration of Democratic candidate Sen. Bernie Sanders, I-Vt.</a>&n=
bsp;So it's not surprising that Weingarten in particular would come up swin=
ging against Trump quickly and vigorously, now that he's the presumptive no=
minee.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
